page.title: 08Woodlands, Henstead
page.content: Between the farms are small areas of woodland which are keepered for cover to encourage the nesting of pheasants. These woodland areas consist mainly of; beech, oak, sycamore, ash and elder trees. Dutch Elm disease killed many.Hawthorn, holly and lilac trees predominate under the main canopy of trees with wild roses, bramble, broom and gorse spreading to accomodate the gaps. Within these woodland areas ferns and nettles dominate with the following flora found just outside the shady areas;docks, bindweed, common sorrel, white campions, buttercups, vetch, clovers, rosebay willowherb, cow parsley, hedge parsley, hogweed, angelica, betony, common field speedwell, plantains, daisies, mayweed, fever-few groundsel, grass and mosses.
